00:51:25.559 --> 00:51:27.308
ADAM FRANK: Well first
of all, I want to--

00:51:27.308 --> 00:51:29.660
there's two ways to think
about the Fermi paradox.

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:32.880
The first one is the idea
that we haven't found anybody.

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:34.850
We've been searching
the stars for signals.

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:36.100
And we haven't found anything.

00:51:36.100 --> 00:51:37.141
And that's just not true.

00:51:37.141 --> 00:51:41.057
I mean there's never really
been a large-scale SETI

00:51:41.057 --> 00:51:41.640
effort, right?

00:51:41.640 --> 00:51:43.260
SETI's never been
really fully funded.

00:51:43.260 --> 00:51:46.050
NASA started to do
a large SETI search.

00:51:46.050 --> 00:51:48.240
And then-- because William
Proxmire had stopped it.

00:51:48.240 --> 00:51:51.660
So as Jill Tarter
says, if the parameter

00:51:51.660 --> 00:51:53.940
space we have to search
for looking for aliens

00:51:53.940 --> 00:51:56.730
is the ocean, we have
looked at a thimble so far.

00:51:56.730 --> 00:51:59.220
So saying that we haven't
found anything that's

00:51:59.220 --> 00:52:00.660
just not scientifically valid.

00:52:00.660 --> 00:52:03.810
So we've barely begun to look,
not just in radio but all

00:52:03.810 --> 00:52:05.427
the other possibilities.

00:52:05.427 --> 00:52:07.760
But if you're asking about
the part of the Fermi paradox

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:10.470
that's why haven't we been
visited, like why don't we

00:52:10.470 --> 00:52:13.410
have evidence for a
civilization, the colonization

00:52:13.410 --> 00:52:16.580
part, that actually we find in
our paper is more of a problem.

00:52:16.580 --> 00:52:19.292
And so the solution to
that right now in the paper

00:52:19.292 --> 00:52:21.750
I think we're leaning towards
is that interstellar travel's

00:52:21.750 --> 00:52:22.410
really hard.

00:52:22.410 --> 00:52:25.710
You don't get many successful
colonization missions.

00:52:25.710 --> 00:52:28.600
Obviously there's some
assumptions here in this.

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:30.900
But again we just did a
paper recently where--

00:52:30.900 --> 00:52:32.380
I did it with Gavin Schmidt
from Goddard Institute

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:34.030
of Space Studies
where we just asked,

00:52:34.030 --> 00:52:36.000
how would you-- this was an
amazing question-- how would

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.124
you know whether there was
a previous technological

00:52:38.124 --> 00:52:40.582
civilization on Earth
20 million years ago?

00:52:40.582 --> 00:52:41.790
