00:52:44.819 --> 00:52:46.860
There would certainly
after-- by 20 million years

00:52:46.860 --> 00:52:50.760
the surface has been
completely rescoured.

00:52:50.760 --> 00:52:52.280
So you're not going
to find ruins.

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:54.330
Or you'd have to look
for isotopic anomalies

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:55.070
or something, which maybe--

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:56.056
AUDIENCE: Monuments on the moon.

00:52:56.056 --> 00:52:56.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:56.550 --> 00:52:57.210
ADAM FRANK: Well,
that's the thing.

00:52:57.210 --> 00:52:58.677
No, no, he's right actually.

00:52:58.677 --> 00:53:00.510
That is exactly what
you'd have to look for.

00:53:00.510 --> 00:53:02.700
So when it comes to
just the Earth itself,

00:53:02.700 --> 00:53:04.440
the Earth has been
weathered so heavily

00:53:04.440 --> 00:53:06.102
and subducted that
it would be hard.

00:53:06.102 --> 00:53:07.560
And so there's been
a couple papers

00:53:07.560 --> 00:53:09.330
on exactly that
about the best place

00:53:09.330 --> 00:53:12.180
to look for this is going
to be on other bodies.

00:53:12.180 --> 00:53:13.050
So-- yes.

00:53:13.050 --> 00:53:14.940
AUDIENCE: So kind
of related to that,

00:53:14.940 --> 00:53:17.617
I think of-- seems to be the one
part where you really do have

00:53:17.617 --> 00:53:19.908
the n equals 1 problem is
what you were talking about--

00:53:19.908 --> 00:53:23.687
the noosphere, right, because
you have all this evidence

00:53:23.687 --> 00:53:25.270
for what happened
previously on Earth,

00:53:25.270 --> 00:53:26.370
because we have
all these other--

00:53:26.370 --> 00:53:26.610
ADAM FRANK: Right

00:53:26.610 --> 00:53:27.660
AUDIENCE: --planets out there.

00:53:27.660 --> 00:53:29.743
But a lot of this stuff,
especially with the Fermi

00:53:29.743 --> 00:53:32.847
paradox, it seems to
me falls prey to this n

00:53:32.847 --> 00:53:34.230
equals 1 problem.

00:53:34.230 --> 00:53:36.470
We are sort of assuming
the intelligent--

00:53:36.470 --> 00:53:41.750
or the civilization is going
to behave like we expect.

00:53:41.750 --> 00:53:43.770
ADAM FRANK: I think that's
what my models tried

00:53:43.770 --> 00:53:45.390
to have no sociology in them.

00:53:45.390 --> 00:53:47.850
It's ba-- the only assumption
was a civilization consumes

00:53:47.850 --> 00:53:48.632
energy to do work.

00:53:48.632 --> 00:53:50.340
That's like the only
assumption in there.

00:53:50.340 --> 00:53:52.120
So I don't need a
noosphere or anything else.

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:52.520
It's just that--

00:53:52.520 --> 00:53:53.936
AUDIENCE: Did you
make assumptions

00:53:53.936 --> 00:53:55.604
about what sort of
energy production?

00:53:55.604 --> 00:53:58.020
ADAM FRANK: There's only so
much kind of energy production

00:53:58.020 --> 00:53:59.750
you're going to get as a
young civilization, right?

00:53:59.750 --> 00:54:01.440
The planet is only
going to afford you--

00:54:01.440 --> 00:54:04.676
if you have z-rays, some like
super hyper, high technology,

00:54:04.676 --> 00:54:06.800
well then you're already
passed this anyway, right?

00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:08.280
If you have warp drives,
you're not really worrying

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:09.270
about your--

00:54:09.270 --> 00:54:12.569
you've probably gotten-- your
science is so far advanced

00:54:12.569 --> 00:54:14.610
that you probably have
already gone through this.

00:54:14.610 --> 00:54:16.484
But if you're a young
civilization like ours,

00:54:16.484 --> 00:54:17.700
you've got biomass.

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:19.500
Or you've got-- you
can burn things.

00:54:19.500 --> 00:54:20.340
There's wind.

00:54:20.340 --> 00:54:21.240
There's solar.

00:54:21.240 --> 00:54:23.130
There's nuclear.

00:54:23.130 --> 00:54:25.957
And there is geothermal, right?

00:54:25.957 --> 00:54:27.040
And that's pretty much it.

00:54:27.040 --> 00:54:29.580
It's-- you can't-- maybe on
some weird planet you could have

00:54:29.580 --> 00:54:31.351
like super magnetic
fields or something.

00:54:31.351 --> 00:54:33.100
So what you can do for
each one of those--

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:35.340
you can evaluate what
the thermodynamic effect

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:36.570
of using it large-scale.

00:54:36.570 --> 00:54:38.820
So for example, there was a
paper done a few years ago

00:54:38.820 --> 00:54:40.800
where they looked
at trying to extract

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:42.950
from wind energy the power--

00:54:42.950 --> 00:54:44.700
what would the
consequences be of powering

00:54:44.700 --> 00:54:46.260
our civilization via wind?

00:54:46.260 --> 00:54:49.350
And what you find is because
of turbulence downstream,

00:54:49.350 --> 00:54:52.329
you end up with the equivalent
of like two degrees of warming

00:54:52.329 --> 00:54:54.120
so which is important
because what it means

00:54:54.120 --> 00:54:58.092
is you can't power civilization
like this and have no impact.

00:54:58.092 --> 00:54:59.550
So this goes back
to nature, right,

00:54:59.550 --> 00:55:00.250
the idea that
there's going to be--

00:55:00.250 --> 00:55:02.458
we're going to be able to
return to pristine nature--

00:55:02.458 --> 00:55:04.380
not with us on
the planet, right?

00:55:04.380 --> 00:55:06.240
You can have lower impact that
you're going to have to be.

00:55:06.240 --> 00:55:08.573
You're going to have to figure
out what kind of impacts.

00:55:08.573 --> 00:55:10.680
But the idea that you can
have no impact is just--

00:55:10.680 --> 00:55:11.740
doesn't make sense.

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:13.823
So yeah, you can evaluate
for every different kind

00:55:13.823 --> 00:55:16.590
of energy source at least make
a cut at what the impact would

00:55:16.590 --> 00:55:17.090
be.

00:55:17.090 --> 00:55:18.449
AUDIENCE: So then one more--

00:55:18.449 --> 00:55:20.490
the assumption you're
making is that civilization

00:55:20.490 --> 00:55:21.990
requires energy.

00:55:21.990 --> 00:55:23.802
That seems to be
that something that I

00:55:23.802 --> 00:55:25.820
think a lot of have--
that seems to be a very

00:55:25.820 --> 00:55:28.270
commonist way of doing this.

00:55:28.270 --> 00:55:30.630
ADAM FRANK: Well, I don't see--

00:55:30.630 --> 00:55:32.440
I mean by-- in some
sense by definition,

00:55:32.440 --> 00:55:33.749
an industrial civilization--

00:55:33.749 --> 00:55:35.790
I mean, Rome-- I'm not
interested in Rome, right,

00:55:35.790 --> 00:55:37.914
because Rome wouldn't Rome
wouldn't push its planet

00:55:37.914 --> 00:55:39.306
into an Anthropocene, right?

00:55:39.306 --> 00:55:41.555
So if a civilization decides
to get up to Rome's level

00:55:41.555 --> 00:55:45.420
and never gets farther, yeah,
that's sort of out of the--

00:55:45.420 --> 00:55:46.110
so you're right.

00:55:46.110 --> 00:55:47.590
That's not what
I'm talking about.

00:55:47.590 --> 00:55:50.177
But if you build an industrial
civil-- if you start har--

00:55:50.177 --> 00:55:52.010
it's all about the
energy per capita, right?

00:55:52.010 --> 00:55:55.320
So right now all of us
have the equivalent of just

00:55:55.320 --> 00:55:58.617
from our home-- when we go
home in our plugs 50 servants.

00:55:58.617 --> 00:56:00.450
That's the energy
equivalent of 50 servants.

00:56:00.450 --> 00:56:02.861
And that doesn't say anything
about your transportation

00:56:02.861 --> 00:56:03.360
or whatever.

00:56:03.360 --> 00:56:04.980
So once the species
gets to the point

00:56:04.980 --> 00:56:07.680
where the per capita
energy use becomes

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:10.532
more than one individual's
worth per individual,

00:56:10.532 --> 00:56:12.490
that's when you're going
to start feeding back.

00:56:12.490 --> 00:56:13.520
So that's the only assumption.

00:56:13.520 --> 00:56:15.350
If they start doing
that, then they sort of

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:17.266
fall into the category
that I'm interested in.

00:56:17.266 --> 00:56:19.210
And then I don't really
care about sociology

00:56:19.210 --> 00:56:20.820
or whether they develop
a noosphere or not.

00:56:20.820 --> 00:56:21.230
Maybe they do.

00:56:21.230 --> 00:56:21.980
Maybe they don't.

00:56:21.980 --> 00:56:23.780
It's just that they're
harvesting energy

00:56:23.780 --> 00:56:27.320
to do the work of building
their civilization.

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:27.842
Yeah.

00:56:27.842 --> 00:56:30.657
AUDIENCE: So do you think
that the current problem we're

00:56:30.657 --> 00:56:33.618
facing is a matter of marketing,
that we have the tools

00:56:33.618 --> 00:56:38.300
and sort of the guidance that
we need to get through if we all

00:56:38.300 --> 00:56:40.250
just somehow banded together?

00:56:40.250 --> 00:56:41.720
ADAM FRANK: Yeah,
I think that's--

00:56:41.720 --> 00:56:43.428
I was just reading
recently about a study

00:56:43.428 --> 00:56:44.390
that sort of showed--

00:56:44.390 --> 00:56:46.190
a super detailed
study-- that you could

00:56:46.190 --> 00:56:51.530
actually power the world with
renewables, with wind, water.

00:56:51.530 --> 00:56:54.320
But so it was a really
detailed plan for doing it.

00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:57.200
Of course, it required
this sort of World War II

00:56:57.200 --> 00:56:59.419
Manhattan-style project
for the entire world.

00:56:59.419 --> 00:57:00.710
And so that's going to be hard.

00:57:00.710 --> 00:57:02.720
But in terms of like
technologically-- man,

00:57:02.720 --> 00:57:03.930
unleash the innovation.

00:57:03.930 --> 00:57:05.180
Let us-- that's one of those--

00:57:05.180 --> 00:57:06.846
when I go out and I'm
talking to people,

00:57:06.846 --> 00:57:09.170
one of the things I'm saying
is like, on one level,

00:57:09.170 --> 00:57:11.420
climate change shows how
awesome we are, right?

00:57:11.420 --> 00:57:14.720
I mean, as-- we've changed the
atmosphere of an entire planet.

00:57:14.720 --> 00:57:17.939
That's pretty good for a
bunch of hairless monkeys.

00:57:17.939 --> 00:57:19.730
And now the question
is are we smart enough

00:57:19.730 --> 00:57:21.469
to innovate our
way into some kind

00:57:21.469 --> 00:57:22.760
of sustainable version of this.

00:57:22.760 --> 00:57:25.010
So it's-- it's not
just marketing though.

00:57:25.010 --> 00:57:25.950
It's deeper than that.

00:57:25.950 --> 00:57:27.110
It's myth, right?

00:57:27.110 --> 00:57:30.020
Human beings always
need stories.

00:57:30.020 --> 00:57:32.690
As somebody said, stories
were the first technology.

00:57:32.690 --> 00:57:34.730
And the problem is
here we have all

00:57:34.730 --> 00:57:36.680
of these-- from the long
history of humanity--

00:57:36.680 --> 00:57:39.410
we have these myths about the
coming of age, about marriage,

00:57:39.410 --> 00:57:41.490
about old age.

00:57:41.490 --> 00:57:43.730
But we don't have any--
and we have creation myths.

00:57:43.730 --> 00:57:47.060
But climate change we don't have
a myth for, because it's new.

00:57:47.060 --> 00:57:48.445
We've never done this before.

00:57:48.445 --> 00:57:49.820
And so what I'm
suggesting is, is

00:57:49.820 --> 00:57:51.230
that a first--
it's not like this

00:57:51.230 --> 00:57:52.800
alone is going to
solve anything.

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:54.350
But if we don't
change the narrative,

00:57:54.350 --> 00:57:57.590
we are stuck arguing with
people about whether we

00:57:57.590 --> 00:57:58.910
change the climate or not.

00:57:58.910 --> 00:58:01.760
From this perspective that
question just disappears.

00:58:01.760 --> 00:58:03.770
It's like, of course,
you changed the climate.

00:58:03.770 --> 00:58:05.390
You built a civilization
that consumes

00:58:05.390 --> 00:58:07.370
a quarter of the
entire biosphere's

00:58:07.370 --> 00:58:09.290
productive capacity.

00:58:09.290 --> 00:58:10.740
What did you expect?

00:58:10.740 --> 00:58:11.614
So I think it just--

00:58:11.614 --> 00:58:14.030
one of things in revolutions--
in scientific revolutions--

00:58:14.030 --> 00:58:16.057
that happen is that
the old questions--

00:58:16.057 --> 00:58:17.640
when you go through
a paradigm shift--

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:18.890
it's not that the old
questions are answered.

00:58:18.890 --> 00:58:20.630
The old questions just don't
even become meaningful anymore.

00:58:20.630 --> 00:58:22.190
People ask a new
set of questions.

00:58:22.190 --> 00:58:24.570
And that's at least what
I'm proposing with this.

00:58:24.570 --> 00:58:25.580
Yeah.

00:58:25.580 --> 00:58:27.664
AUDIENCE: This might
tread a little bit more

00:58:27.664 --> 00:58:29.330
philosophical although
there are clearly

00:58:29.330 --> 00:58:30.260
philosophical ideas that--

00:58:30.260 --> 00:58:30.968
ADAM FRANK: Yeah.

00:58:30.968 --> 00:58:32.552
AUDIENCE: you put up there too.

00:58:32.552 --> 00:58:34.135
You mentioned that
you're an optimist.

00:58:34.135 --> 00:58:40.340
And piggybacking on the question
about marketing I sort of--

00:58:40.340 --> 00:58:47.310
my worry is that
there is not, in fact,

00:58:47.310 --> 00:58:49.970
at present in human
thinking the idea

00:58:49.970 --> 00:58:51.900
that humanity is, in
fact, a single species.

00:58:51.900 --> 00:58:52.608
ADAM FRANK: Yeah.

00:58:52.608 --> 00:58:56.510
AUDIENCE: We can sort of
think about this as a collab--

00:58:56.510 --> 00:58:58.630
as a truly
