00:59:04.685 --> 00:59:08.160
Do you have thoughts that make
you more optimistic on that?

00:59:08.160 --> 00:59:10.540
Is it sort of-- and I'm not
saying that blind faith would

00:59:10.540 --> 00:59:11.170
be unreasonable.

00:59:11.170 --> 00:59:11.540
Perhaps--

00:59:11.540 --> 00:59:11.840
ADAM FRANK: Yeah.

00:59:11.840 --> 00:59:12.276
[LAUGHS]

00:59:12.276 --> 00:59:13.570
AUDIENCE: There's another
way to think about this.

00:59:13.570 --> 00:59:15.986
ADAM FRANK: Yeah, oh, I mean
it's gotten us through a lot,

00:59:15.986 --> 00:59:16.650
right?

00:59:16.650 --> 00:59:20.590
But no, actually so I think
when you look across species,

00:59:20.590 --> 00:59:24.430
I feel confident in my
bones that there have been

00:59:24.430 --> 00:59:25.840
other civilizations, right?

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:27.640
Scientifically I can only
go far as the probabilities

00:59:27.640 --> 00:59:28.900
that this has happened before.

00:59:28.900 --> 00:59:30.700
And what I imagine
is the ones that

00:59:30.700 --> 00:59:36.250
make it have either the
evolutionary background

00:59:36.250 --> 00:59:38.560
to have the right kinds of
behaviors-- maybe hive mind.

00:59:38.560 --> 00:59:40.390
It's much easier if
you're a hive mind

00:59:40.390 --> 00:59:42.790
to make it through this than
if you're the kind of thing

00:59:42.790 --> 00:59:43.730
that we are.

00:59:43.730 --> 00:59:46.570
But the other possibility is
that you evolve under pressure,

00:59:46.570 --> 00:59:47.230
right?

00:59:47.230 --> 00:59:50.230
Selective pressure is
what determines evolution.

00:59:50.230 --> 00:59:52.720
And perhaps this is
the agent by which we

00:59:52.720 --> 00:59:55.470
start to create new behaviors.

00:59:55.470 --> 00:59:57.130
Sure, the Paris Accord was weak.

00:59:57.130 --> 00:59:59.740
But the Paris Accord was
also remarkable in the sense

00:59:59.740 --> 01:00:02.600
that we've got every
country to sign this thing.

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:03.620
So that was a beginning.

01:00:03.620 --> 01:00:06.370
And then we took
a giant step back.

01:00:06.370 --> 01:00:08.470
But so I think--

01:00:08.470 --> 01:00:11.890
the Anthropocenes
may be the agent

01:00:11.890 --> 01:00:14.050
for some kinds of species,
perhaps like ours,

01:00:14.050 --> 01:00:15.880
to develop new
evolutionary behaviors that

01:00:15.880 --> 01:00:16.970
allow them to get through.

01:00:16.970 --> 01:00:18.080
And if you make it through--

01:00:18.080 --> 01:00:18.610
it's weird.

01:00:18.610 --> 01:00:20.770
Like if I put my hat on as
a dad, I'm like, oh, my god.

01:00:20.770 --> 01:00:21.580
We've got to make it through.

01:00:21.580 --> 01:00:22.040
[LAUGHS]

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:23.610
But if I put my hat on as
an astronomer I'm like,

01:00:23.610 --> 01:00:24.670
eh, some make it through.

01:00:24.670 --> 01:00:25.170
Some don't.

01:00:25.170 --> 01:00:26.628
AUDIENCE: Nothing
special about us.

01:00:26.628 --> 01:00:28.520
ADAM FRANK: Yeah,
nothing special about us.

01:00:28.520 --> 01:00:29.020
All right.

